    {
        "content": "<p>On the nlab is stated, in various places, that infinite-dimensional manifolds are smooth sets, i.e. sheaves on the (essentially small) site of Cartesian spaces.<br>\nI have an infinite-dimensional, separable Banach space in my hands (call it <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span>), and I want to check if it's 'smooth'. Do you have any idea on how to use it to get a sheaf on that site?<br>\nAn idea is to simply take maps <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>→</mo><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Bbb R^n \\to P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.664392em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span>, but which kind of maps? The smooth ones, one might say, but how do I define what a smooth map into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> is?</p>",
        "id": 210493480,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1600419232
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Smooth maps to Banach spaces are unambiguously defined (unlike for general locally convex spaces). But you might be thinking of the sheaf of continuous functions valued in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span>? This is the diffeology that takes all continuous functions and declares them to be \"smooth\".</p>",
        "id": 210592146,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1600481060
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275932\">Matteo Capucci</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Infinite-dimensional.20manifolds.20as.20smooth.20sets/near/210493480\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>An idea is to simply take maps <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>→</mo><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Bbb R^n \\to P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.664392em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span>, but which kind of maps? The smooth ones, one might say, but how do I define what a smooth map into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> is?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The usual concept of a smooth map between Banach spaces (e.g. a smooth map from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{R}^n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.664392em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> to some other Banach space) is one that has derivatives of arbitrary orders, where the derivative involved is the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fr%C3%A9chet_derivative\">Frechet derivative</a>.</p>",
        "id": 210599104,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1600494149
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh well <span aria-label=\"thinking\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f914\" role=\"img\" title=\"thinking\">:thinking:</span> yeah it didn't occur to me to use Frechet derivatives, but it feels like the correct notion</p>",
        "id": 210609580,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1600513307
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I was thinking that past Fréchet, there are inequivalent notions, the best one is <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Michal-Bastiani+smooth+map\">https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Michal-Bastiani+smooth+map</a>, but for Banach everything is peachy.</p>",
        "id": 210646371,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1600570807
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes.    There's a weaker concept of derivative even for maps between Banach spaces (or Banach manifolds), where you don't require <em>uniform</em> convergence of the difference quotient for the derivative: it's called the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gateaux_derivative#Definition\">Gateaux derivative</a>.   But this doesn't even define a linear transformation between tangent spaces unless you demand it does (thereby eliminating some examples).  So I've always used the Fréchet derivative.</p>",
        "id": 210671572,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1600615777
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here's a paper listing <strong>seven</strong> different types of derivatives in locally convex spaces: <a href=\"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF01585512\">https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF01585512</a> and they all agree with the Fréchet derivative in finite dimensions!</p>",
        "id": 210685188,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1600635697
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is starting to feel like another entry in <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229111-general/topic/How.20many.20structures.3F\">this topic</a> <span aria-label=\"joy\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f602\" role=\"img\" title=\"joy\">:joy:</span></p>",
        "id": 210685453,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1600636084
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah, but I'm not sure we have classified (or even can!) how many definitions of derivative there are :-)</p>",
        "id": 210689727,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1600643035
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The upshot is, if <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275932\">@Matteo Capucci</span>  is working with Hilbert, Banach or Fréchet manifolds, then after realising we need something <em>like</em> the Fréchet derivative, where it is continuous in two slots, not just at each point, or in each direction,  then there are no more choices. </p>\n<p>If one goes out past Fréchet spaces as models for charts, then there are choices. Convenient calculus is a popular one, and fits well with diffeological spaces. But from the point of view of global analysis, the Michal–Bastiani calculus is \"better\". Or at least, in the circles I move close to, that what people prove theorems with, since it is a stronger notion, I believe.</p>",
        "id": 210689859,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1600643235
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Wow I didn't know there were so many options!</p>",
        "id": 210708240,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1600672946
    }
]